406→                           Conjectured by Erdős, Faudreee, and Ordman. This would be best possible, as witnessed by dividing the vertices of $K_n$ into two equal parts and colouring all edges between the parts red and all edges inside the parts blue.<br><br>The answer is yes, proved by Gruslys and Letzter <a href="#cite-GrLe20-76" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('GrLe20','76'); return false;">[GrLe20]</a>.<br><br>In <a href="#cite-Er97d-76" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er97d','76'); return false;">[Er97d]</a> Erdős also asks for a lower bound for the count of edge-disjoint monochromatic triangles in single colour (the colour chosen to maximise this quantity), and speculates that the answer is $\geq cn^2$ for some constant $c&gt;1/24$.
